data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, new implicit span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

Expression trees **cannot represent span-based method calls**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` to force the old `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast in the expression
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use Enumerable explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);
```

The same issue can affect `.Reverse()` on arrays (now binds to the in-place `Span` overload). The fix pattern is the same — qualify with `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` or `.AsEnumerable()`.
